WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.490 --> 00:00:03.945
Professor Charles
Bailyn: We had gotten,

00:00:03.945 --> 00:00:07.100
at the end of last time,
to the Big Rip.

00:00:07.100 --> 00:00:10.072
This is where the
ever-expanding Cosmological

00:00:10.072 --> 00:00:13.314
Constant--which is,
of course, a contradiction in

00:00:13.314 --> 00:00:15.727
terms.
If you imagine that dark energy

00:00:15.727 --> 00:00:19.090
is not a Cosmological Constant,
that it's actually increasing

00:00:19.090 --> 00:00:21.220
in time, rips everything to
shreds.

00:00:21.220 --> 00:00:24.285
The Universe becomes infinite
in size in a finite amount of

00:00:24.285 --> 00:00:26.400
time and everything gets pulled
apart.

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:31.600
What I want to start by doing
today is to go back and do that

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:33.420
again slowly,
okay?

00:00:33.420 --> 00:00:39.450
Because I think this is not a
simple line of reasoning that

00:00:39.450 --> 00:00:43.445
leads you to this.
So, let's go all the way back

00:00:43.445 --> 00:00:46.615
to what we know about the
Universe from observing

00:00:46.615 --> 00:00:49.390
galaxies, supernovas,
things like that.

00:00:49.390 --> 00:00:55.565
We know that the Universe is
expanding and that,

00:00:55.565 --> 00:00:59.100
we know.
Hubble already figured that out.

00:00:59.100 --> 00:01:05.862
We know this from the Hubble
Law, and from other--just,

00:01:05.862 --> 00:01:13.251
in general, from the study of
standard candles at relatively

00:01:13.251 --> 00:01:18.140
low redshift.
So, distances out to,

00:01:18.140 --> 00:01:23.266
I don't know,
Z of less than 0.2,

00:01:23.266 --> 00:01:26.419
or so.
You can't tell the difference

00:01:26.419 --> 00:01:29.950
between an accelerating or a
decelerating Universe.

00:01:29.950 --> 00:01:33.382
All you know is that it's
expanding, and you can figure

00:01:33.382 --> 00:01:38.232
out how fast it's expanding.
Now, the next question then

00:01:38.232 --> 00:01:42.661
becomes the rate of expansion.
Is the rate of expansion

00:01:42.661 --> 00:01:44.880
changing?
Is it accelerating?

00:01:44.880 --> 00:01:47.780
Is it decelerating?
What's going on there?

00:01:47.780 --> 00:01:52.536
And so, you want to compare
acceleration versus

00:01:52.536 --> 00:01:56.154
deceleration,
which is a fancy word,

00:01:56.154 --> 00:01:59.670
as you know,
for slowing down.

00:01:59.670 --> 00:02:03.607
And deceleration:
this is relatively easy to

00:02:03.607 --> 00:02:07.940
grasp.
This is what happens because of

00:02:07.940 --> 00:02:09.939
matter.
Matter exists.

00:02:09.939 --> 00:02:13.440
It's got gravitational force,
and gravitational force tends

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:16.304
to hold things together.
So, if you've got something

00:02:16.304 --> 00:02:18.702
that's moving apart,
and there's some gravitational

00:02:18.702 --> 00:02:20.956
force, it'll tend to hold it
together, and thus,

00:02:20.956 --> 00:02:23.342
slow it down.
Most of the matter,

00:02:23.342 --> 00:02:26.468
it turns out,
is this weird dark matter,

00:02:26.468 --> 00:02:30.876
which we don't understand,
but that's what's responsible

00:02:30.876 --> 00:02:34.324
for the deceleration.
If you're going to make it go

00:02:34.324 --> 00:02:37.102
faster, you need something much
weirder that pushes outward,

00:02:37.102 --> 00:02:39.775
that has repulsive force.
This, we believe,

00:02:39.775 --> 00:02:45.569
actually exists.
This, we label dark energy.

00:02:45.569 --> 00:02:48.940
And so, the question of,
"is it accelerating or is it

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:52.893
decelerating," is basically a
question of how much dark energy

00:02:52.893 --> 00:02:55.810
is there versus how much matter
is there,

00:02:55.810 --> 00:02:59.394
because the more--if you have
more of this than this,

00:02:59.394 --> 00:03:02.219
then it will accelerate and
vice versa.

00:03:02.219 --> 00:03:08.168
And what we have discovered by
supernovae observations with

00:03:08.168 --> 00:03:14.450
redshifts of greater than 0.3,
and by now, out to about a

00:03:14.450 --> 00:03:19.527
redshift of 1,
or so, demonstrate that--well,

00:03:19.527 --> 00:03:24.189
what exactly does this say?
Let's go slowly.

00:03:24.189 --> 00:03:31.006
In the past,
the Universe was expanding more

00:03:31.006 --> 00:03:39.408
slowly than it is now,
and therefore--those three dots

00:03:39.408 --> 00:03:46.699
are the mathematical symbol for
therefore.

00:03:46.699 --> 00:03:52.626
Therefore, the Universe is
accelerating,

00:03:52.626 --> 00:03:59.160
and therefore,
there's more dark energy than

00:03:59.160 --> 00:04:03.119
there is matter.
And you'll recall,

00:04:03.119 --> 00:04:05.317
we did the little pie chart of
the Universe,

00:04:05.317 --> 00:04:07.616
and it turns out,
it's 3/4 dark energy and 1/4

00:04:07.616 --> 00:04:10.988
matter.
And those proportions are

00:04:10.988 --> 00:04:17.829
determined by the rate at which
the Universe is accelerating.

00:04:17.829 --> 00:04:20.449
Not the rate at which it's
expanding, but the rate at which

00:04:20.449 --> 00:04:22.527
it's accelerating,
because that's the change in

00:04:22.527 --> 00:04:27.076
the expansion.
Fine, so far--or maybe it isn't

00:04:27.076 --> 00:04:28.915
fine.
I should pose that as a

00:04:28.915 --> 00:04:32.810
question.
Fine?

00:04:32.810 --> 00:04:36.777
This is the basic premise of
where we had gotten to about a

00:04:36.777 --> 00:04:38.199
week ago.
Yes sir?

