00:37:21.043 --> 00:37:23.335
of .8 to 1.
Now, in principle,

00:37:23.335 --> 00:37:27.047
you could go out and make a
whole bunch of--you know,

00:37:27.047 --> 00:37:30.617
measure 10,000 of these things
at a redshift of .5,

00:37:30.617 --> 00:37:33.330
and try and distinguish that
way.

00:37:33.330 --> 00:37:35.735
Okay.
So, how are we going to figure

00:37:35.735 --> 00:37:36.940
this out?
The space telescope,

00:37:36.940 --> 00:37:38.659
kind of, finds these things one
at a time.

00:37:38.659 --> 00:37:41.150
It's going to be awfully tough
to make this distinction.

00:37:41.150 --> 00:37:45.729
But let me introduce you to two
projects currently underway,

00:37:45.729 --> 00:37:48.989
the goal of which is to figure
this out.

00:37:48.989 --> 00:37:52.349
They do the exact two things
that we've just been talking

00:37:52.349 --> 00:37:54.343
about.
One is designed to go

00:37:54.343 --> 00:37:58.164
deep-to-high redshift,
and the other is designed to do

00:37:58.164 --> 00:38:01.480
many, many, many,
at intermediate redshift.

00:38:01.480 --> 00:38:07.568
So, there is something called
the--so, there's a space

00:38:07.568 --> 00:38:15.042
mission, space telescope.
This is called JDEM,

00:38:15.042 --> 00:38:23.349
